                     </role>
                  </name>
                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Don Anderson papers relating to John Steuart Curry, 1942-1973.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>Correspondence regarding Curry, with Chris Christensen, Kathleen Curry, Vachel Davis, Lawrence Schmeckebier, and others; a letter from Curry to Christensen, 1946; 13 photographs of Anderson, Curry and others in Montana, ca. 1941; a photograph of Jimmy Demetral with his portrait painted by Curry; and printed material. Two photographs (previously part of Photos of Artists Collection II) of Curry sketching Anderson's daughter, Susan Anderson (age 9), while working on the mural "Kansas Homestead, " General Land Office, Dept. of the Interior. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Unknown</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>
resource.title: Don Anderson papers relating to John Steuart Curry, 1942-1973.
resource.abstract: Correspondence regarding Curry, with Chris Christensen, Kathleen Curry, Vachel Davis, Lawrence Schmeckebier, and others; a letter from Curry to Christensen, 1946; 13 photographs of Anderson, Curry and others in Montana, ca. 1941; a photograph of Jimmy Demetral with his portrait painted by Curry; and printed material. Two photographs (previously part of Photos of Artists Collection II) of Curry sketching Anderson's daughter, Susan Anderson (age 9), while working on the mural "Kansas Homestead, " General Land Office, Dept. of the Interior.

                     <role>

                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Gallatin County bicentennial oral history project collection, 1974-1976.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>Eighty-three tape recorded interviews (and a few typed transcripts) with senior citizens of Bozeman and Gallatin County, Mont. Topics cover a wide variety of historical subjects including agriculture, amusements, business, industry, merchants, churches, communications, education, electrical power, ethnic groups, the Depression, homemaking, immigrants, Native Americans, medicine, Montana State College, organizations, frontier and pioneer life, politics and government, prominent families, religion, social life and customs, Spanish American War, transportation, weather and natural disasters, World War I, and World War II. Places mentioned include Belgrade, Bozeman, Bridger Canyon, Chestnut, Churchill, Gallatin Canyon, Manhattan, Salesville, Springhill, Three Forks, and Yellowstone National Park. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Montana State University Bozeman Library</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
